We employed two methods here, including calculating the genetic differentiation (Fst) between gamecock chickens (TLF, LX, Laos, and BN chickens) and non-gamecocks (chickens except RJF and gamecock chickens) and the pooled-heterozygosity score (Hp) within gamecock chickens upon sliding windows, to identify the genomic regions under selection in gamecocks population. Considering the gamecock populations harbor relatively high genome nucleotide diversity and heterozygosity in chickens, we narrowed down the window size and step size to 20Â Kb and 10Â Kb when calculating both Weir-Fst value and Hp score of each window. We eliminated the windows with SNPs less than 5 to ensure detective accuracy. The top 1% outliers of bins were regarded as the putative genomic regions under selection, and further annotated using Ensembl BioMart tool (https://oct2018.archive.ensembl.org/biomart/martview/fcee6700cde0db959bc30ef4fc9d839a). Those putatively selected genes from each method were then submitted to gProfiler (https://biit.cs.ut.ee/gprofiler/gost) for function enrichment analysis with options âOrganism: Gallus gallusâ and âUser threshold: 0.05â. Both the Fst value and Pooled-heterozygosity score of each bin were Z-transformed according to the formula below and further Manhattan-plotted with in-house R scripts:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
